<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>LSUIElement</key>
    <true/>
    <key>NSHighResolutionCapable</key>
    <true/>
    <key>NSSupportsAutomaticGraphicsSwitching</key>
    <true/>

    <!--
        macOS privacy usage descriptions.

        These are required IN ADDITION to the entitlements declared in
        `python-entitlements.plist` (which let the signed Python sidecar
        ASK for the corresponding TCC permissions). Without a usage
        description string here, macOS does not surface the permission
        prompt the first time the app touches the device. The result is
        silent failure: the audio capture API succeeds but every frame
        is digital silence (with the occasional bit of analog noise
        leaking through, which reads as random small jumps on a level
        meter - exactly the symptom we hit on USB-mode conversation,
        where the Python daemon runs as a tray sidecar on this Mac
        rather than on the robot's Pi).

        The Wi-Fi mode wasn't affected because in that path the daemon
        runs on the robot itself; macOS isn't in the audio capture
        path at all.

        The strings are user-facing: macOS displays them verbatim in
        the permission prompt, so they describe WHY the app needs
        each device.
    -->
    <key>NSMicrophoneUsageDescription</key>
    <string>Reachy Mini needs access to the microphone so it can relay your voice to the robot during conversations.</string>
    <key>NSCameraUsageDescription</key>
    <string>Reachy Mini may use the camera for vision-based features. Decline to keep the conversation working without video.</string>
</dict>
</plist>
